{"word":"φίλος","slug":"φίλος","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<b><el>φίλος, η, ον</el></b> [<a class=\"G\" href=\"S:✎ orig.\">orig.</a> undetermined] ‘in a close relationship with another’, as opposed to casual acquaintanceship<b><p class=\"pp3\"/>—<pp>a.</pp></b> as <a class=\"G\" href=\"S:✎ adj.\">adj.</a> <b>friendly, kindly disposed <a href='B:510 19:31'>Ac 19:31</a>.<p class=\"pp3\"/>—<pp>b.</pp></b> as noun <b>friend<p class=\"pp4\"/>—<pp>α.</pp></b> <el><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:ὁ\">ὁ</a> <a class=\"S\" href=\"S:φίλος\">φίλος</a></el> <b><a href='B:470 11:19'>Mt 11:19</a></b> and <a class=\"G\" href=\"S:✎ oft.\">oft.</a> in Lk. In <b><a href='B:490 23:12'>Lk 23:12</a>; <a href='B:500 19:12'>J 19:12</a></b> <el>φ.</el> signifies political amity with implication of the noun <el><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:ἐχθρός\">ἐχθρός</a></el> as its opposite. <b><p class=\"pp4\"/>—<pp>β.</pp></b> <el>ἡ <a class=\"S\" href=\"S:φίλη\">φίλη</a></el> <b><a href='B:490 15:9'>Lk 15:9</a>.</b> <center id=\"nav_bottom\"> <a id=\"left_arrow\" href=\"S:φιλοπρωτεύω\">&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;</a> <a id=\"bottom_home\" href=\"S:#1.Table of Contents\">&emsp;&emsp;</a> <a id=\"right_arrow\" href=\"S:φιλοσοφία\">&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;</a> </center> "}]}